  <annotation>This legend is closely related to Jens Peter's story of buried treasure (JPP 4.17). Unlike that more elaborate story, this one is a simple summary of events. The action takes place at a different mound, and the ring is housed in the more religiously important church in the market town of Hj&#xF8;rring. The folk etymology for the town name derived from the found treasure is a common feature of many stories of supernatural contact (KMP 1.19). 

     The name Kloonh&#xF8;j, identified in the topographical index as Klovnh&#xF8;j, should be emended to Klovenh&#xF8;j, a mound several hundred meters to the north and east of Hj&#xF8;rring church.</annotation>
  <danish_manuscript>Der gaar ogsaa Sagn om, at der
skal have v&#xE6;ret en Drage i Kloon-
h&#xF8;j og der fik de en Guldring af en
Kiste. S. sak Kisten ned i H&#xF8;jen i 
gien men Ringen beholdt de og den
er sat ind i St. Kathrine Kirke i
Hj&#xF8;rring. Deraf skal Hj&#xF8;rring have
Navn, det var f&#xF8;rst H&#xF8;jring.</danish_manuscript>
  <english_manuscript>There was also a legend that there was supposed to be a dragon in Kloonh&#xF8;j near Hj&#xF8;rring and they got a gold ring from a chest. Then the chest sank down into the mound again but they kept the ring, and it was placed in St. Kathrine's church in Hj&#xF8;rring. The town is supposed to have gotten its name from this, since it was originally H&#xF8;jring.</english_manuscript>
  <danish_publication>Der gaar ogsaa Sagn om, at der skal have v&#xE6;ret en Drage i Kloonh&#xF8;j ved Hj&#xF8;rring. De grov efter en Skat og fik fat i en Guldring af en Kiste. Men da de snakkede, sank Kisten ned i H&#xF8;jen igjen, men Ringen beholdt de, og den er sat ind i St. Kathrine Kirke i Hj&#xF8;rring. Deraf skal Byen have faaet sit Navn, for det var f&#xF8;rst H&#xF8;jring.</danish_publication>
  <english_publication>There was also a legend that there was supposed to be a dragon in Kloonh&#xF8;j mound near Hj&#xF8;rring. They dug after a treasure and got hold of a gold ring on a chest. But when they spoke, the chest sank down into the mound again, but they kept the ring, and it was placed in St. Catherine&#x2019;s church in Hj&#xF8;rring. The town is supposed to have gotten its name from this, since it was originally H&#xF8;jring.</english_publication>
